[4] Nigeria: number of doctors - correction
Date: 8 Dec 2014
From: Ebere Okereke <Ebere.Okereke@phe.gov.uk> [edited]


In the ProMED bulletin (Ebola virus disease - West Africa (221): Liberia, S. Leone, Nigerians, orphans), you mention that Nigeria only has only 4000 registered medics. I think you will find that this is incorrect. The Nigerian Medical Council claims 35 000 members, and the CIA world fact book estimated that Nigeria had 0.4 doctors/1000 population in 2008 (ref. http://www.indexmundi.com/g/r.aspx?c=ni&v=2226; which, assuming a population of 170 million, puts the number of doctors at 68 000.

--
Dr Ebere Okereke
GMC No: 4289177
Consultant in Communicable Disease Control
West Yorkshire Health Protection Team, UK
<Ebere.Okereke@phe.gov.uk>

[I got that statistic from: List of Registered Medical Practitioners - statistics http://www.gmc-uk.org/doctors/register/search_stats.asp. Top 20 countries of qualification.

On reflection, this must be the number of Nigerian doctors registered in the UK. I regret the error.

On the other hand, another online site reports:

Africa's Brain Drain: Nigerian Medical Doctors, by John Campbell, 29 Oct 2013:
"Dr. Enabulele said that of 71 740 medical doctors registered with the Medical and Dental Council, only 27 000 are practicing in Nigeria." http://blogs.cfr.org/campbell/2013/10/29/africas-brain-drain-nigerian-medical-doctors

But in any case, even if all 600 Nigerians arriving in West Africa are doctors, they would not severely deplete the number in the country as I had feared. - Mod.JW]

